Hello Maple Shade Families,

The storm knocked out power on the north side of town. Steinhauer school has no power.

At this time, Steinhauer school will have a two hour delay including the preschool program at Steinhauer. Steinhauer will begins its day at 9:48. Preschool at Steinhauer will begins its day at 11:00 am. No breakfast will be served but lunch will be served. Bus pickups will be 2 hours later than normal. Little Shaders at Steinhauer will also have a 2 hour delay.

If we do not get the power restored, I will call and email with another message. I understand the power is out in a lot of the town, be safe and please call the schools with any concerns about getting to school.

Thank you!

Beth Norcia

Please see the attached video shared by Yocum Elementary School, "The Quiet Lesson." The Quiet Lesson was inspired by one of Maple Shade's paraprofessionals - Jesse O'Brien. He works with Zachary Hutchinson who has Krabbe Disease. Jesse went quiet for a week to experience what it was like for Zach. Then his teachers, speech therapist, and classmates decided they wanted to join in. Our music teacher Jeff Cope filmed and edited the video.

Video: https://youtu.be/6SAvL7ISp4E

#MSWildcatPride

Dear Maple Shade Families,

I wanted to give an update on our schools for tomorrow, Wednesday, February 20, 2019. With the snow forecasted to start potentially around 11:00 am, it is difficult to make a definite call this early. I know a phone call for a half-day session in the early am is too difficult to arrange for our families. At the very least, the Maple Shade School District will have a half-day session tomorrow, February 20, 2019.

I will review the projected forecast in the am before I make the call to close school for the day. You will receive the call before 6:00 am if we are closing for the day.
Breakfast will be served but no lunch will be served.
PM half-day pre-school is canceled for tomorrow.

Below are the 4-hour session times-

Howard Yocum dismissal- 1:05

Maude Wilkins dismissal- 12:30

Steinhauer dismissal - 12:00

High school dismissal- 11:50

Preschool full day- 1:00

Preschool half-day am dismissal-11:10

The Maple Shade Schools will have a 4-hour session in all school’s tomorrow, February 20, 2019, and I will review the forecast in the am.

Maple Shade High School has been named to the College Board’s 9th Annual AP® District Honor Roll. The Honor Roll recognizes 373 school districts in the U.S. and Canada that have increased access to AP coursework while maintaining or increasing the percentage of students earning scores of 3 or higher on AP Exams.

We’re proud to have been named to the College Board’s 9th Annual AP® District Honor Roll for our efforts to expand access to AP coursework and improve student performance on AP Exams.

The Maple Shade School District is committed to expanding access to AP® coursework to students of all backgrounds, improving performance, and supporting success. Thank you to our students and staff for their continued work towards this goal.

We are pleased to announce the continuation of the half-day integrated preschool program for the 2018/2019 school year. We are offering the opportunity for a limited number of students to be educated alongside preschoolers with disabilities in an inclusion setting.

The program will be offered five days per week from 12:25 to 2:40 pm at Maude Wilkins Elementary School. Children must be 3 years of age and no older than 5 years old on/before September 30th, 2018. If the number of applicants exceeds the number of available spots, a lottery will be held to determine entry into the program. The lottery will take place on May 31, 2018. Families will be notified of their application status by mail, by June 8, 2018.

If you are interested in applying for our integrated preschool class, please click the link below to print and fill out the application and return to our office.

Application: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rQBNJ5cdZ2TSWfoJOcGTp0ZiU6_cgRSSNM4NMOwMU4o/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
Despite a wintry weekend, fourteen students from MSHS's History Club attended the 47th Annual YMCA Model United Nations Conference in Hershey, PA. At the conference, the students authored resolutions and defended them to solve international problems not limited to equal access to education, human trafficking, crisis resolution, and environmental mandates.

The students have been working for months to research their respective assigned countries' positions on topics such as the ones listed above. Maple Shade High School was one of several "Outstanding Delegations" and Britnee Ferrier's assigned country, Australia, won "Premier Country." This year's delegation was the most active in thirteen years! Thank you to Mrs. Danowski & Mrs. Giberson for their continued support.

MSHS Environmental classes win first place in the Philadelphia Zoo's Albert M. Greenfield Foundation UNLESS Contest.

The Maple Shade High School Environmental classes came in FIRST place out of 236 schools that participated in the 2017 UNLESS project contest for the high school division.

Thank you to Joe Andl and the township of Maple Shade, Rick Winters, Solitude Lake Management and all the teachers and students who supported out the project.

post_text:
The MSHS Environmental classes have been involved in the UNLESS project ran through the Philadelphia Zoo. The project creates awareness about an endangered species and an environmental problem. Students are to create a project that spreads awareness about the topics they choose. This year the classes choose the Panamanian Golden Frog and Water Conservation. Their focus for the water conservation aspect of the project is Steinhauer Pond.

Students created flyers to educate awareness about the importance of water conservation and ways individuals can help at their own homes. The next step was to clean up the pond. The students went down to the pond and cleaned as much of the area inside the pond and around the pond as they could. They will also be planting aquatic plants in my to make the pond more sustainable.

post_text:
Students in 6th Grade Science worked in teams and designed/constructed solar ovens using a pizza box and other materials. Students used materials that would absorb as much heat as possible. Also, students utilized their knowledge of physical and chemical properties/changes to help make their designs. Students tested the ovens with smore's ingredients and positioned their ovens according to the angle of the sun.

Thank you, Miss Ketchen and Mrs. Gimello for your help with this project!

Shout out to, "The famous Yellow Submarine" of Maple Shade for their donation of pizza boxes!

Next Generation Science Standards covered by our students in this experience:

-Develop a model that predicts and describes changes in particle motion, temperature, and state of a pure substance when thermal energy is added or removed.

-Undertake a design project to construct, test, and modify a device that either releases or absorbs thermal energy by chemical processes.

The MSHS History Club participated in its eleventh Model United Nations conference sponsored by the Burlington County YMCA, January 8-10. Fifteen students from our delegation traveled to Hershey, PA and worked to prepare solutions to global issues plaguing the world. They represented various countries and served in different committees along with nearly 2000 students from PA, NJ, and DE. Our delegation, led by Youth Secretariat, Julie Welsh, represented Maple Shade well. Many students co-authored resolutions that were passed in their respective committees. We're looking forward to next year's conference!

Top (left to right): Sean McGlinn, Brandon Motter, Braedon Domansky, Joseph Finn, Carly Leonard, Julie Welsh, and Cassandra Rogers

Bottom (left to right): Goldy Cubacub, Emily Kirchner, Alyssa Garrett, Marisa Lazar, Alexis Short, Jamie Noone, Jenna Bennett, and Danielle Borja

How tall is your tree?

Take a look at the attached pictures to explore students' trees. Students in Ms. Baker's class at Steinhauer had to work collaboratively in groups of 3-4 to plan, create and revise how to use plastic straws and modeling clay to construct the tallest tree.

Students learned that the trees need a sturdy foundation and less clay at the top in order to make their structure the tallest.

The winning tree was 24 inches tall!

post_text:
Students as Biomedical Engineers at Steinhauer (compliments of Ms. Waterhouse's class)

Students were given a problem and had to act as biomedical engineers to develop an "enteric" pill coating. Students had a limit of four ingredients to use to create their coating (flour, sugar, corn starch, and vegetable oil). They were also given a maximum number of spoonfuls that they could use for each ingredient to make their mixture. Students created recipes (using fractions) for their coatings and then tested their recipes by observing its effectiveness in protecting a piece of candy (skittles) in an environment (sprite) that simulates the stomach's environment. Before the activity students learned about the Digestive System during the cell unit and chemical properties/reactions during the matter unit. Students also learned about how engineers and pharmacists have to develop coatings for medications that are safe for humans and prevent stomach pain.

Special thanks to Miss Paolini, Mrs. Kanakis, Mrs. Lyons, and Mrs. Schlotterbeck for helping make this project successful!

Veterans Day Events at Maude Wilkins

Staff and students at Maude Wilkins were given a presentation on Veterans day from various servicemen from the many branches of the armed services. They spoke to the students about their careers and what Veterans day is about (picture below). The students and staff were very thankful and appreciative of all the hard work the servicemen and women do for our country.

Students in Mrs Asch’s class recognized the importance of Veterans day by setting up their white table and reading the book America's White Table by Margot Theis Raven (picture below). Students built strong connections to the book and the importance of Veterans day.

Thank you to Mrs. Payton and the right choice committee for organizing our first reward for our students, the Mini Bootcamp. Volunteers from the armed services put together a mini boot camp for the students to participate in (picture below). Once they were done they enjoyed some Camouflage Rice Krispy treats received their dog tags, and their certificate of completion.

Congratulations to Mr. Ormsby and the Maude Wilkins’ staff. Eighteen pumpkin catapults represented the third and fourth grade classrooms. A variety of designs were tested and used in the first ever Maude Wilkins’ school wide STEM Challenge. The winning classroom at each grade level will receive a Kindle Learning Station and a Pizza Party. Ms. Schuehler’s 3rd grade class had the longest catapult of the day, measuring in at a distance of 41 feet, 4 inches.

Great job to all staff and students as their excitement and engagement were at a high level during the competition. The classes did an excellent job in the weeks leading up to today. They implemented the design/engineering thought process and used failure as a measure towards success. The attached pictures highlight the event.

post_text: STEM UPDATE: After one week, Mrs. Kanakis' and Miss Ketchen's Language Arts classes were finally able to see their Mummified Apple results!! Students observed and measured the apples in the different mixtures and made many conclusions. The best mixture to mummify an apple is to mix 1/2 a cup of Epsom Salt with 1/2 a cup of Table Salt and submerge the apple into the mixture. The apple was able to stay just about the same size and weight while not rotting or molding but releasing the moisture. Students then compared and contrasted the mummifying techniques used in Ancient Egypt to the process they went through in the experiment. They decided against eating the apples for lunch!

post_text: Awesome group of edus and ARI interns helped enhance our Yocum playground. Thank you to all who helped!
shared_text:
Howard Yocum Elementary School
August 12, 2015 at 4:21 PM ·

The Yocum playground got a fresh new look today along with an additional piece of playground equipment for our students to enjoy! We were extremely fortunate to have so many volunteers come out and help with this project, especially our friends from the business community.

ARI summer interns partnered with Yocum to build and donate a recycled tire dinosaur for their playground. Project leader, Steven Reitz, coordinated the effort with his mother, Yvonne, who is Yocum's Vice-Principal. Steven led a team of volunteers from ARI, the school, and the community in Yocum’s effort to improve their playground and Go Green. Reitz said, “Giving back and working for the benefit of children has given us the biggest reward of the summer. I can’t wait to come back and see the kids enjoying their new dinosaur.”

ARI, a part of the Holman Automotive Group, is a global vehicle fleet management leader headquartered in Mount Laurel, N.J.

#YocumSchool #WildcatPride #ARIFLEET

Thank you!

Beth Norcia, superintendent

post_text:
Dear Parents and Community Members:

As you may have heard, I will be retiring as of September 1. At its meeting last night, our Board of Education voted to appoint Mrs. Beth Norcia to the position of Superintendent of Schools, effective September 1. Mrs. Norcia has been employed in the district for seventeen years. She has worked here as a teacher, assistant principal and elementary principal of two schools. Mrs. Norcia and I will work together over the next few months to ensure a smooth transition and a productive start to the school year. I am fully confident she will be an outstanding leader for the district. I know you will join me in wishing her well in her new position.

Sincerely,
Michael Livengood, Superintendent

post_text: Congratulations to Maple Shade High School softball player Danielle Carey. Danielle collected her 100th career hit, smashing a double down the third base line in her first at-bat during Tuesday's game. Her teammates and coaches are extremely proud of her accomplishment!

post_text: Maple Shade High School is proud to offer its students a diverse range of elective classes, including an elective course in Sports Medicine. Recently, students from Mrs. von Leer's Sports Medicine classes took a trip to the Drexel University Medical School cadaver lab to see how medical students study anatomy first hand.

post_text: It is going to be a beautiful sunny day in Maple Shade! The Maple Shade varisty girls softball team will be playing Riverside, AT RIVERSIDE (this was previously scheduled to be a home game.) Also, at Maple Shade High School, the junior high track team will be hosting a meet with Harrington Middle School and Cinnaminson Middle. Both JV and varsity lacrosse are away today versus Northern Burlington while the middle school lacrosse team takes on Indian Mills Middle School in Shamong.

May 3, 2014 at 9:28 PM ·

Students from Maple Shade High School are representing both Maple Shade and the entire state of New Jersey at the DECA Natrional Competition in Atlanta, Georgia. Congratulations to them and the greater Maple Shade community wishes them good luck in competition!
